They might say that it would be good if doctors
you know joined MÃ©decins Sans FrontiÃ¨res,

00:24:40.460 --> 00:24:44.940
right?
But with writers and artists, one does hear

00:24:44.940 --> 00:24:46.889
this.
Why though?

00:24:46.889 --> 00:24:55.250
What is it about let's say writers that give
them any kind of special access into this?

00:24:55.250 --> 00:24:58.980
So do you have any feelings about that?

00:24:58.980 --> 00:25:08.220
&gt;&gt;Personally, well I don't think there should
be expressional art in any form to the degree

00:25:08.220 --> 00:25:12.710
that
you know if it is a social issue is what motivates

00:25:12.710 --> 00:25:16.720
you or that spurs you on, then that's great.
But if you are an artist, and that's not your

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:21.799
emphasis, I don't think there's anything wrong
with that.

00:25:21.799 --> 00:25:24.350
Cuz art is just free expression.

00:25:24.350 --> 00:25:28.130
Harold: Yeah, good point.
But is the free expression really free or

00:25:28.130 --> 00:25:33.019
is it secretly complicitis?
I mean, take an exaggerated situation like

00:25:33.019 --> 00:25:39.250
the Third Reich.
You know, a lot of artists left Germany when

00:25:39.250 --> 00:25:41.450
this was going on.
But some didn't.

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:49.889
Some Aryan artists continued to produce.
And they weren't writing about the war or

00:25:49.889 --> 00:25:54.070
doing images about the war.
They were writing about the homeland and the

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:56.030
country,
and the kinds of mythologies that have always

00:25:56.030 --> 00:26:02.740
been you know evident in Germany.
Now, were they simply expressing themselves,

00:26:02.740 --> 00:26:08.340
or by turning their back on what was going
on, were they being complicitis?

00:26:08.340 --> 00:26:13.950
&gt;&gt; Complicitis, but I look at it more as perhaps
survival.

00:26:13.950 --> 00:26:20.259
In a sense that you know, those artist might
have agreed with the Third Reich ideology.

00:26:20.259 --> 00:26:27.450
But then again they decided to stay, it might
have been just a matter of survival.

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:33.190
Of not being able to have the courage to speak
truth to the powers.

00:26:33.190 --> 00:26:37.139
Harold: Yeah, sure, no I think that is well
put.

00:26:37.139 --> 00:26:40.889
&gt;&gt;The thing is that I'm trying to take this
position where I'm not judging.

00:26:40.889 --> 00:26:45.710
But after the same time as a human being I
you know I do judge.

00:26:45.710 --> 00:26:50.809
That particular ideology is totally offensive
to me, and I would think that anybody would

00:26:50.809 --> 00:26:52.970
come against it.
But life has so many shades of grey.

00:26:52.970 --> 00:27:02.019
And you know, people are put in so many difficult
situations, it's just really hard to say if

00:27:02.019 --> 00:27:06.409
they were being complicit or supporting that
ideology.

00:27:06.409 --> 00:27:12.960
Or in a sense, just trying to survive.
Not having the courage to speak out.

00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:18.670
Harold: Yeah, no, understood.
I think what at least theoretically gives

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:26.019
an artist a particular access that people
in other profession might not so readily have

00:27:26.019 --> 00:27:32.990
is that the artist cultivates dream space
and cultivates rumination.

00:27:32.990 --> 00:27:39.230
And spends time thinking in ways that aren't
permitted to let's say people who work from

00:27:39.230 --> 00:27:44.820
8 to 6.
And the insights that come from this kind

00:27:44.820 --> 00:27:51.909
of contemplation are different and often useful
to you know, to articulating.

00:27:51.909 --> 00:27:57.149
Also artists, if they have any kind of reputation,
have easy access to media.

00:27:57.149 --> 00:28:01.480
You know that other people don't have.
Now take the situation of AIDS.

00:28:01.480 --> 00:28:08.820
When AIDS was happening, you know you're a
young woman, and so you were very young then

00:28:08.820 --> 00:28:14.980
if you were even born.
The kind of hate that was let lose was quite

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:20.740
extraordinary, even for a country like this.
The hate that was addressed, especially to

00:28:20.740 --> 00:28:26.379
gay men then, that's one act up and grand
fury came together,

00:28:26.379 --> 00:28:33.250
And gay people, but not exclusively gay people
bracketed what they were doing, and they decided

00:28:33.250 --> 00:28:40.320
to try to expropriate the expropriator.
And use the very weapons, you know the propaganda

00:28:40.320 --> 00:28:50.220
against the people and institutions who were
demonizing people with AIDS.

00:28:50.220 --> 00:28:58.200
And that's when the battle turned.
And I think even though an entire generation

00:28:58.200 --> 00:29:08.029
was lost, I do believe it would have been
a lot worse if act up and grand fury didn't

00:29:08.029 --> 00:29:13.100
poster St. Patrick's cathedral where the then
cardinal was making --

00:29:13.100 --> 00:29:19.240
was about to give some talk demonizing AIDS,
people with AIDS and so on.

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:21.759
I think it would have been a lot worse than
it actually was.

00:29:21.759 --> 00:29:29.970
So there art intervention actually was very
useful.

00:29:29.970 --> 00:29:36.060
Sometimes it can't be measured in that way.
And even when it can't be measured, you know,

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:42.059
I think there's a valid argument for it.
But you know, having said this, I do agree

00:29:42.059 --> 00:29:45.580
with you.
That I don't know that the imperative actually

00:29:45.580 --> 00:29:51.750
applies to everyone.
There are some people who are incapable you

00:29:51.750 --> 00:29:52.750
know as artists.

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:54.049
&gt;&gt;I was gonna say.
They are wired to personally.

00:29:54.049 --> 00:29:55.049
Harold: Yeah.

00:29:55.049 --> 00:30:01.960
&gt;&gt; You know, I do believe artists have that
obligation to address this issue.

00:30:01.960 --> 00:30:09.039
In fact I was thinking my daughter is a theatre
major at University San Francisco.

00:30:09.039 --> 00:30:13.129
And part of that major is theatre as social
justice.

00:30:13.129 --> 00:30:14.750
And that part is combined.

00:30:14.750 --> 00:30:15.750
Harold: Yeah

00:30:15.750 --> 00:30:22.139
&gt;&gt; And as she comes home, you know in her
youthful vigor, she talks about her art and

00:30:22.139 --> 00:30:26.830
how it influences and how she really wants
to change things.

00:30:26.830 --> 00:30:31.980
And that is a perfect complement.
But at the same time, I think about some artist

00:30:31.980 --> 00:30:39.309
who just wants to get on television and be
on "American Idol" and do something like that.

00:30:39.309 --> 00:30:43.080
They're an artist, but I don't think they're
pushing any kind of social agenda.

00:30:43.080 --> 00:30:48.120
Harold: No I'm happy to hear that.
But you know, as far as changing, effecting

00:30:48.120 --> 00:30:57.769
change.
One can't ever expect the response to be commensurate

00:30:57.769 --> 00:31:02.490
with the effort.
I think at a time like now, it's a question

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:07.580
of bearing witness.
Of you know, nobody knows what's gonna happen

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:11.669
to the works we do.
Whether they'll be absolutely in the hands

00:31:11.669 --> 00:31:15.960
of managers, you know corporate managers.
Or whether they'll be somehow alive on the

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:19.480
net.
Assuming that the net has some degree of freedom,

00:31:19.480 --> 00:31:26.830
you know 25 years or 30 years from now.
But the notion of bearing witness is a very

00:31:26.830 --> 00:31:31.920
important one, especially in a time like now
because change has been so accelerated.

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:38.409
Just think, the last 15 years how people think,
particularly in technology of course, has

00:31:38.409 --> 00:31:43.789
affected the way the world is viewed.
Language, you know, has changed radically,

00:31:43.789 --> 00:31:48.360
very rapidly because of the very short hand
ways.

00:31:48.360 --> 00:31:53.179
We don't look at events directly anymore,
not that we're always easily able to,

00:31:53.179 --> 00:31:57.620
we look at them in a mediated way through
a screen or through a small screen.

00:31:57.620 --> 00:32:02.029
But what's going on is instead of looking
there, there's violence there, we look here

00:32:02.029 --> 00:32:07.549
and we see the mediated form of the violence
which of course is gonna have some lies and

00:32:07.549 --> 00:32:13.499
some you know some changes that are.
So the idea of being an artist who bears witness,

00:32:13.499 --> 00:32:18.320
I don't think that's negligible.
But again, you're right, there are people

00:32:18.320 --> 00:32:23.140
who aren't wired to do that.
There aren't artists, there are some artists

00:32:23.140 --> 00:32:29.870
who aren't wired to do that.
And even if they live in a toxic, you know,

00:32:29.870 --> 00:32:35.789
environment such as the Third Reich.
Perhaps one can argue that you know, they're

00:32:35.789 --> 00:32:39.030
still doing the best they can.
I think that's possible.

00:32:39.030 --> 00:32:45.629
&gt;&gt; Here's another question.
It's sort of falls under the same umbrella.

00:32:45.629 --> 00:32:52.289
How does the influence that corporate or government
sponsors pull on the current artist.

00:32:52.289 --> 00:32:56.010
Oh, I'm sorry, did I?

00:32:56.010 --> 00:33:04.019
Harold: No, I know what you mean.
If you're doing an exhibit which is virulently

00:33:04.019 --> 00:33:10.720
interrogative of what government and corporations
are doing and it's being shown at the museum

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:14.490
of modern art in New York, and it's sponsored
by Mobil, right?

00:33:14.490 --> 00:33:17.220
And Mobil does sponsor it.
What does that mean?

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:22.179
I mean are you being complicit?
I mean when you see something on the wall

00:33:22.179 --> 00:33:26.890
in the museum sponsored by Mobil, you don't
look at it in the same way as you might if

00:33:26.890 --> 00:33:32.870
you saw it in some sort of handout.
The same thing applies to writers arguably

00:33:32.870 --> 00:33:38.419
who publish a book with Simon and Schuster.
You know which professes to be you know interrogative.

00:33:38.419 --> 00:33:43.710
Simon and Schuster wouldn't do it unless they
misread it, which is very likely.

00:33:43.710 --> 00:33:49.320
And is the fact that it has that imprint immediately
compromised?

00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:53.470
It's a hard question.
I mean the fact is you know we're living at

00:33:53.470 --> 00:33:59.490
a very imperfect time.
And there are all kinds of quibbles and small

00:33:59.490 --> 00:34:06.669
sacrifices that one makes.
If you see Guernica in the museum of modern

00:34:06.669 --> 00:34:12.429
art or some other place, do you think about
the small Spanish town that's being bombed

00:34:12.429 --> 00:34:24.569
by the fascists?
Or do you just see another exquisite experiment

00:34:24.569 --> 00:34:29.240
by Picasso there.
That's part of the question, yeah.

00:34:29.240 --> 00:34:37.050
&gt;&gt; Well, I think if I understand things properly,
what's going on is really a question of whether

00:34:37.050 --> 00:34:42.869
an omission can be an act.
So if you have a duty to do something and

00:34:42.869 --> 00:34:48.649
when omitting is safe, then an artist has
a duty to be socially active.

00:34:48.649 --> 00:34:56.210
Whether failing to perform that duty is you
know really something that you know can be

00:34:56.210 --> 00:35:00.550
you know display worthy.
And what I find interesting is that in European

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:07.109
countries, omission is generally considered
to be at least in law something culpable.

00:35:07.109 --> 00:35:11.060
So if you see someone drowning, and you could
save them by throwing them a rope and you

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:18.869
don't, that actually can be prosecuted.
But in America, no state can be prosecuted.

00:35:18.869 --> 00:35:22.290
Harold: Yeah, that's an interesting point.
Very subtle.

00:35:22.290 --> 00:35:30.410
Yeah, you know, there isn't any ongoing tradition
of socially activist art in the United States.

00:35:30.410 --> 00:35:34.660
I mean there've been moments.
There were the Transit Analysts who were against

00:35:34.660 --> 00:35:41.560
the slave trade.
There were the people associated with IWW.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:48.079
There were the 30's communists, most of whom
changed when Stalin came to power.

00:35:48.079 --> 00:35:56.550
There certainly, you know in the 60's, for
that blip of a period from 1966 let's say

00:35:56.550 --> 00:36:04.650
to 1972, there were young people who at least
in France came close to overthrowing the country.

00:36:04.650 --> 00:36:12.430
But there were as you know, in '68, there
were protests and very powerful ones across

00:36:12.430 --> 00:36:19.410
the world in places you wouldn't expect.
But, and including America.

00:36:19.410 --> 00:36:24.140
But generally speaking, if you compare the
United States with France.

00:36:24.140 --> 00:36:30.180
If you compare it even with England.
If you compare it with Germany.

00:36:30.180 --> 00:36:39.309
There hasn't been any ongoing vital ongoing
social activist response in art.

00:36:39.309 --> 00:36:43.760
Just spots.
But. and that itself is an interesting question.

00:36:43.760 --> 00:36:48.970
Why that should be?
And I think the response to that is complex.

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:58.059
It has to do with a number of factors that
govern, you know, this country and--

00:36:58.059 --> 00:37:02.109
--and sustain the way this country functions.

00:37:02.109 --> 00:37:08.579
&gt;&gt; I mean socially it has to tie in the sort
of American mythology about personal freedom.

00:37:08.579 --> 00:37:09.579
Harold: Yeah.

00:37:09.579 --> 00:37:14.190
&gt;&gt; So, here's the question.
Why do recurring folks on the [inaudible ]list

00:37:14.190 --> 00:37:22.880
The outrage of the current society, and the
responsibility of the artists in these times

00:37:22.880 --> 00:37:27.690
seem to both be clear things.
Poverty is a timeless issue.

00:37:27.690 --> 00:37:32.569
How does it fit into your general argument?

00:37:32.569 --> 00:37:38.130
Harold: How does the notion of poverty fit
into these?

00:37:38.130 --> 00:37:44.380
Well, you know I think, you know I read last
words from people on death row.

00:37:44.380 --> 00:37:49.610
I think one of the important points is to
see these people from the subject position.

00:37:49.610 --> 00:37:54.650
And I've dealt with this in different ways,
extreme ways where I've talked about serial

00:37:54.650 --> 00:37:58.980
killers and so on.
And It's very easy to demonize people.

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:06.510
And also I've written about art brut people
who are accounted, I use that verb deliberately

00:38:06.510 --> 00:38:11.700
who are accounted mad.
And, but do some very unusual art.

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:19.630
Art that's valued, but sometimes marginalized.
I try to see them from the subject position.

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:28.829
That is to imagine them talking or even to
find places where they've articulated

00:38:28.829 --> 00:38:32.390
sentences or in certain instances art, visual
art.

00:38:32.390 --> 00:38:39.819
I think seeing them from the subject position
and hearing them is important.

00:38:39.819 --> 00:38:46.490
Whether it's a political prisoner.
Whether it's a very very poor person who's

00:38:46.490 --> 00:38:51.960
handing out some homeless leaflet.
I think insofar as possible, and it's not

00:38:51.960 --> 00:38:57.920
always easily possible as you know to hear
them from the subject position.

00:38:57.920 --> 00:39:04.950
Instead of having them objectified, and hearing
the same kinds of platitudes of moralistic

00:39:04.950 --> 00:39:09.630
platitudes about them.
I think that's an important first step.

00:39:09.630 --> 00:39:15.140
And when you hear them, you know what I did
is I went back to the records of Texas prisoners

00:39:15.140 --> 00:39:19.770
who were executed.
And I actually got to the final statements,

00:39:19.770 --> 00:39:23.540
which again I treated.
I changed in certain ways.

00:39:23.540 --> 00:39:29.860
They were extraordinarily articulate and very
powerful and very poetic.

00:39:29.860 --> 00:39:32.900
None of that's heard.
You know, they're just, you know most of them

00:39:32.900 --> 00:39:39.160
as you would expect were Mexican or African
American or American Indian.

00:39:39.160 --> 00:39:44.079
And none of that was heard.
They were allowed to have these last words

00:39:44.079 --> 00:39:48.119
the way they were allowed to have a last meal,
but all of its forgotten.

00:39:48.119 --> 00:39:51.990
But I didn't want it to be forgotten, so I
rescued it.

00:39:51.990 --> 00:39:55.630
And I put it in a different context.
Part of what I read was from that.

00:39:55.630 --> 00:40:01.740
But I've a large thing called Death in Texas.
A large text where I actually, I have about

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:06.030
30 prisoners who are about to be executed
talk.

00:40:06.030 --> 00:40:12.000
And I inserted some unusual things in it that
didn't belong there.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:24.119
I actually took a 19th century person from
a German institution for the mental incapacitated,

00:40:24.119 --> 00:40:29.109
and I inserted that.
Made some changes into the prisoners, the

00:40:29.109 --> 00:40:32.440
death row prisoners.
Nobody was able to distinguish that.

00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:36.089
Nobody said a word about that, it was published
in a number of places.

00:40:36.089 --> 00:40:44.109
Madam, that would be the first step I think.
To allow them to articulate from the subject

00:40:44.109 --> 00:40:46.480
position.
You know without interfering.

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:53.240
I think that itself is not a small first step.
Because when you hear, when you allow yourself

00:40:53.240 --> 00:40:59.849
to hear, you know or see what people who are
otherwise severely marginalized are doing

00:40:59.849 --> 00:41:10.490
then even the coldest least feeling, least
compassionate people are not likely, but liable

00:41:10.490 --> 00:41:20.400
to be moved.
And that's not unimportant I think.

00:41:20.400 --> 00:41:22.579
Yeah?

00:41:22.579 --> 00:41:37.440
&gt;&gt; As mass communication sort of moves seemingly
to increasing form of illiteracy [inaudible]

00:41:37.440 --> 00:41:40.819
social [inaudible]
Are examples [Inaudible] texts becoming harder

00:41:40.819 --> 00:41:42.099
to find?

00:41:42.099 --> 00:41:48.420
Harold: Well they're becoming very different.
Everything is very abbreviated.

00:41:48.420 --> 00:41:54.349
Which makes it easier for me because I'm deliberately
working in very short units.

00:41:54.349 --> 00:41:59.680
I chose 50 words rather than the number of
characters of twitter because that didn't

00:41:59.680 --> 00:42:05.440
allow me enough access.
But by choosing 50 words, it forced me into

00:42:05.440 --> 00:42:10.640
closing and opening of certain spaces.
Yeah, in a traditional sense certainly, the

00:42:10.640 --> 00:42:15.890
discourse has changed.
It's much more dumbed down than it was.

00:42:15.890 --> 00:42:21.069
And the references are much more restricted.
You never find any high cultural references

00:42:21.069 --> 00:42:25.200
or rarely there.
I mean if you read the American newspapers,

00:42:25.200 --> 00:42:28.670
or American you know whether they are online
or off.

00:42:28.670 --> 00:42:32.940
So it's much more parochial, you know than
it was.

00:42:32.940 --> 00:42:38.270
The advantage of it is that it's brief.
Because newspapers you know are ape computers

00:42:38.270 --> 00:42:43.940
now, so everything looks like U.S. World,
U.S. News today.

00:42:43.940 --> 00:42:50.799
You know, everything looks like that now.
And so it's easier to plunder, you know.

00:42:50.799 --> 00:42:55.579
It's easier to bushwack these texts because
of their abbreviation.

00:42:55.579 --> 00:43:00.329
But yeah, they don't point in as many directions
as you'd like them to.

00:43:00.329 --> 00:43:05.980
On the other hand, if they were cultivated,
and pointed in those other directions, they

00:43:05.980 --> 00:43:11.819
might not interest you know us plunderers,
you know in the same way.

00:43:11.819 --> 00:43:21.120
Because they would be viable, you know, insofar
as you know that kind of news can be viable.

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:25.690
That's a subtle question, it's a good question.

00:43:25.690 --> 00:43:31.200
&gt;&gt; Here's another question, and it goes to
your book.

00:43:31.200 --> 00:43:35.031
What inspired you to use the twitter format?
And do you use twitter at all?

00:43:35.031 --> 00:43:41.240
Harold: Do I, the last part was am I on twitter
myself?

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:47.270
I have an account there, I don't I haven't
followed it up because I have,

00:43:47.270 --> 00:43:56.369
between my writing and fiction international,
I'm on so many different social network sites

00:43:56.369 --> 00:44:01.630
sometimes that I'm not doing them myself.
But the assistance on the Journal Fiction

00:44:01.630 --> 00:44:10.359
International are.
I use it, I use it in an emblematic way.

00:44:10.359 --> 00:44:18.450
As representing the new communication in "Anti-Twitter"
I mean I could have said anti facebook.

00:44:18.450 --> 00:44:21.770
Of course, I wanted to use twitter because
of the abbreviation.

00:44:21.770 --> 00:44:25.650
The extreme abbreviation.
And I think it's like text messaging.

00:44:25.650 --> 00:44:29.220
That's what's been changing you know, the
language.

00:44:29.220 --> 00:44:34.010
Now if you asked me what I think about the
language being changed, I have mixed feelings.

00:44:34.010 --> 00:44:41.950
I like some of the innovations that lets say
rap singers and sports people have used where

00:44:41.950 --> 00:44:46.630
they play around with their name.
T-Mac for Tracy McGrady and so on, I think

00:44:46.630 --> 00:44:55.569
that's amusing and I like that.
But the language otherwise is changing in

00:44:55.569 --> 00:45:06.309
ways that are you know funny and theatrical,
but I think finally leaving us less leverage

00:45:06.309 --> 00:45:11.670
to be expressive than we'd like to be.
You know, I like listening to it, but it's

00:45:11.670 --> 00:45:18.980
 -- the leverage is getting narrower and narrower.
